<paragraph blockId="10.[151,1436,1953,2014]" lastBlockId="11.[151,1437,151,464]" lastPageId="11" lastPageNumber="482" pageId="10" pageNumber="481">
TCEC made additional observations on the shelters of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Collins &amp; Larsen" authorityYear="1994" box="[774,974,1953,1978]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Abantis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="481" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bamptoni">
<emphasis box="[774,974,1953,1978]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="481">Abantis bamptoni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
on 
<taxonomicName box="[1019,1209,1953,1978]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Phyllanthaceae" genus="Uapaca" kingdom="Plantae" order="Malpighiales" pageId="10" pageNumber="481" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="kirkiana">
<emphasis box="[1019,1209,1953,1978]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="481">Uapaca kirkiana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName authorityName="" authorityYear="1820" box="[1225,1398,1953,1978]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Phyllanthaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Malpighiales" pageId="10" pageNumber="481" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Phyllanthaceae</taxonomicName>
) in Mutinondo Wilderness, Mpika, Zambia, in 
<date box="[649,801,1990,2014]" pageId="10" pageNumber="481" value="2014-01">January 2014</date>
(
<figureCitation box="[818,987,1989,2014]" captionStart-0="FIGURE 13" captionStart-1="FIGURE 14" captionStartId-0="11.[151,250,1636,1658]" captionStartId-1="12.[151,250,1062,1084]" captionTargetBox-0="[151,1436,519,1611]" captionTargetBox-1="[151,1436,555,1038]" captionTargetId-0="figure@11.[151,1436,519,1611]" captionTargetId-1="figure@12.[151,1436,555,1038]" captionTargetPageId-0="11" captionTargetPageId-1="12" captionText-0="FIGURE 13. Early leaf shelters of Abantis bamptoni on Uapaca kirkiana, Mutinondo Wilderness, Zambia, Jan 2014 [TCEC]. 1, view of whole leaf (about 25 cm long); 2, hatched ovum, with site of first shelter and instar 1 feeding; 3, shelter 2 freshly cut and turned over; 4, as  3, but one day later; 5, as  4, viewed from the side." captionText-1="FIGURE 14. Final leaf shelter of Abantis bamptoni on Uapaca kirkiana, Mutinondo Wilderness, Zambia, Jan 2014 [TCEC]. 1, shelter in situ; note the caterpillar head is just visible; 2, view of whole leaf (about 25 cm long)." httpUri-0="https://zenodo.org/record/855823/files/figure.png" httpUri-1="https://zenodo.org/record/855825/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="481">Figures 13â€“14</figureCitation>
). Observations were made on the first two shelters of one individual (
<figureCitation box="[510,624,151,176]" captionStart="FIGURE 13" captionStartId="11.[151,250,1636,1658]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,519,1611]" captionTargetId="figure@11.[151,1436,519,1611]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURE 13. Early leaf shelters of Abantis bamptoni on Uapaca kirkiana, Mutinondo Wilderness, Zambia, Jan 2014 [TCEC]. 1, view of whole leaf (about 25 cm long); 2, hatched ovum, with site of first shelter and instar 1 feeding; 3, shelter 2 freshly cut and turned over; 4, as  3, but one day later; 5, as  4, viewed from the side." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/855823/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="482">Figure 13</figureCitation>
). The whole leaf in situ in Figure 13.1 shows the site of the first leaf shelter, and the second leaf shelter. Figure 13.2 is an enlargement of the first shelter and surrounding area, with feeding damage mostly to the leaf surface areas, seldom perforating the leaf. The hatched ovum can be seen, adjacent to the hole where the shelter lid was cut out, and it appears that the shelter covered the small patch of surface feeding to the right of the cut portion, as there is evidence of silking over that area. Since the priority of the neonate caterpillar would be to make its leaf shelter, we suggest that the first feeding thereafter was on the floor of the shelter. The flap of the shelter is missing; this suggests the flap may have been detached by the caterpillar, since normally when a the first shelter is unoccupied due to the death of the caterpillar, the flap remains attached for a long time, and it can be quite hard to open it for examination.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<caption httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/855823/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="482" targetBox="[151,1436,519,1611]" targetPageId="11">
